This doc scopes out what to do when fully_shard is called on a module with spmd_types - annotated parameters.

The starting annotation scenarios are (generalizing to other data axes, TP-style axes, e.g. EP):
1) Invariant on FSDP axis
2) Sharded on TP axis
3) Invariant on FSDP axis, Sharded on TP axis

Approach 1 (style of D94907792): FSDP is DTensor, restoring original spmd_types annotation.

    This approach keeps FSDP internals in DTensors, saving the spmd_types sharding spec before sharding,
and restoring it for compute after unsharding. This keeps FSDP internals the same, and also allows DTensor placements
to propagate to gradients / optimizer state (e.g. DTensor.zeros_like()).
    This requires translating the starting spmd_types annotation into DTensor placements, and letting FSDP operate on
an existing mesh dim (cases 1, 3), or concatenating another (case 2).
    Similarly to D94907792, we add no_typecheck() around FSDP internals.

Approach 2: keep everything in spmd_types.

    This makes added FSDP sharding in spmd_types, amending the partition spec of parameters, instead of converting to DTensors.
I am not sure how much change this requires to FSDP internals. We also add no_typecheck() for internals, just adding the extra sharding on FSDP axis,
and ignoring what happens under the hood. At unshard time the sharding is removed, and the pre-fully_shard spmd_types placement restore.
    Propagating placements to optimizer state / gradients requires a typecheck context.

The 2 approaches appear similar in that FSDP's main job is restoring pre-shard spmd_types annotations, and disabling typechecking on FSDP internals.
The main difference is whether storage-time representation is DTensor or spmd_types.
